data.content:
Your assertions work but use generic `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which produces unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False." MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with clear diagnostics.

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|--------|-------|---------|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "Expected 3, got N" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Fails clearly if 0 or 2+ matches |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine with `Assert.IsTrue` since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API — just make sure `IsNotEmpty` runs first so `.All()` doesn't vacuously pass on an empty collection.
